```javascript
function checkPrimesInArray(numbersArray) {
  // Iterate over each element in the given array
  for (const num of numbersArray) {
    let isPrime = true;

    // Check if the number is prime using a basic algorithm
    // If the number has any divisor other than 1 and itself, it's not prime
    if (num > 1) {
      for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
        if (num % i === 0) {
          isPrime = false;
          break;
        }
      }
    } else {
      // Numbers 0 & 1 aren't considered primes
      isPrime = false;
    }

    // Log prime numbers to the console
    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(`${num} is a prime number`);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
checkPrimesInArray([3, 6, 7, 9, 11]);
```

This example will log "7 is a prime number" because only 7 from the provided array is a prime number. The function can handle arrays of different lengths containing up to five numbers, logging any primes it finds among them. However, keep in mind this is a simplified approach to primality testing, more efficient algorithms exist like the Sieve of Eratosthenes or Miller-Rabin test for larger scale applications.

