Here's a simple C++ program demonstrating how to count the occurrences of a given target word from a text file, line by line:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>
#include <regex>

int main() {
    std::string target_word; // The specific word to search for
    std::cout << "Enter the target word to search: ";
    std::cin >> target_word;

    std::ifstream input_file("text_file.txt"); // Open the text file
    if (!input_file) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file!" << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    std::smatch match; // For regex matching
    std::regex pattern(std::regex("(\\b" + target_word + "\\b)", std::regex_constants::icase)); // Case-insensitive regex pattern

    int count = 0;
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(input_file, line)) {
        while ((std::regex_search(line, match, pattern))) {
            ++count; // Increment count on each successful match within the line
            line = match.prefix().str() + match.suffix(); // Remove matched word from current line for next iteration
        }
    }
    input_file.close();

    std::cout << "\nThe target word '" << target_word << "' appears " << count << " times in the text file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program uses regular expressions to perform case-insensitive searches for the specified `target_word`. It opens the text file named `text_file.txt`, iterates through lines, and checks for matches using the provided regex pattern. Each time a match is found, the counter increments, and the matched word is removed from the current line to avoid double counting in the same line. Finally, it prints out the total number of occurrences of the target word in the text file. Make sure to replace `"text_file.txt"` with your actual filename containing the text you want to analyze.
